## How To Investigate A Wazuh Alert

### Step 1 — Read The Summary
```
Rule ID      → What rule triggered
Level        → How serious is it
Description  → What happened in simple terms
```

### Step 2 — Check Key Fields
```
agent.name   → Which device generated this
agent.ip     → IP of that device
timestamp    → When did it happen
```

### Step 3 — Read The Event Detail
```
targetUserName  → Who was involved
processName     → What program caused this
logonType       → What type of login
eventID         → Windows event identifier
```

### Step 4 — Apply O-M-C
```
O → What exactly do I see?
M → What does this tell me?
C → What action do I take?
```

---

## Real Investigation Example

### Alert Received
```
Rule 60106 — Windows Logon Success
Level 3 — Low
T1078 — Valid Accounts
targetUserName: SYSTEM
processName: C:\Windows\System32\services.exe
logonType: 5
```

### O-M-C Analysis
```
O → SYSTEM account logged on via services.exe
    Logon Type 5 — service logon
    Level 3 — low severity

M → Windows starting its own internal services
    SYSTEM account used by Windows itself — not humans
    services.exe is legitimate Windows process

C → False Positive ✅
    Normal Windows service activity
    No action needed — document and close
```

